                <p rend="flushleft">I <hi rend="italic">Hearing of the Yugoslav and Italian
                        Representatives</hi>
                </p>
                <p>It was <hi rend="italic">agreed</hi>, on the proposal of the Chairman, that the
                    representatives of Yugoslavia and Italy should be admitted to the Council to
                    express their views on Article 16 and that the Yugoslav representative should be
                    heard first.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">M. Simić</hi>, Foreign Minister of Yugoslavia, read a
                    statement in English and submitted a proposal concerning Article 16 of the Draft
                    Peace Treaty (see doc. <gloss target="#t_CFM46NY1">CFM (46) (NY)</gloss>
                        5),<note n="63" xml:id="d306fn63">
                        <hi rend="italic">Infra</hi>.</note> together with a map of a new line
                    proposed for the frontier between Yugoslavia and Italy.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">M. Tarchiani</hi>, Ambassador of Italy to Washington, read
                    a statement in English (see doc. <gloss target="#t_CFM46NY1">CFM (46)
                        (NY)</gloss> 6).<note n="64" xml:id="d306fn64">
                        <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1038">p. 1038</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="1055" n="1031" xml:id="pg_1031"/>
                <p>The Representatives of Yugoslavia and Italy then left the Council Room.</p>
                <p>It was <hi rend="italic">agreed</hi> that the statements made by the Yugoslav and
                    Italian Representatives and the new Yugoslav proposals for Article 16 of the
                    Italian Treaty would be examined by the Council when it considered for a second
                    time the Paris Conference recommendation on that Article. It would then be open
                    also to any member of the Council to move an amendment to the Council’s previous
                    decision on the frontier line.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">II <hi rend="italic">Recommendations of the Paris Conference on
                        the Peace Treaty With Italy</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Continuation of First
                        Reading</hi>)<note n="65" xml:id="d306fn65">
                        <ref target="frus1946v04#pg_889">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p.
                            889</ref>. The locations of specific articles cited in this section are
                        indicated in the annotations to the United States Delegation Minutes of this
                        meeting, <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The Council resumed its consideration of the unagreed Articles with the following
                    results:</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Annex III. Ceded Territories</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Consideration <hi rend="italic">deferred</hi> as no recommendation received from
                    the Paris Conference.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Annex VI. Part B, Insurance</hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Referred to the Deputies</hi> for further study.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Annex VII. Part III, Negotiable Instruments</hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Adopted</hi>.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Annex VII. Part V, U.S. Proposal</hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Reserved</hi> for further study.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Annex VIII. Judgments</hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Adopted</hi>.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">III <hi rend="italic">Next Meeting of the Council</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Friday, November 8, at 3:30 p.m.</p>
                <p>Agenda: Review of points still outstanding in the Peace Treaty with Italy.</p>
